  "prompt": "What does it mean when your left eye twitches?",
  "response": "An eye twitch, known medically as myokymia, can happen for several reasons, and a twitch in the left eye (or either eye) is generally not a cause for concern. Common causes include:\n\n1. **Fatigue:** Lack of sleep or excessive fatigue can lead to twitching.\n2. **Stress:** Increased stress or anxiety levels can trigger muscle spasms in the eye.\n3. **Caffeine:** Excessive intake of caffeine or stimulants can cause your eyes to twitch.\n4. **Eye Strain:** Spending prolonged periods on screens or not using the correct prescription glasses can lead to eye strain.\n5. **Dry Eyes:** If your eyes are dry, which can be due to extended screen time or certain medications, this might trigger twitching.\n6. **Nutritional Deficiencies:** Deficiencies in certain nutrients, particularly magnesium, can cause muscle twitching.\n7. **Allergies:** Eye allergies can result in itchy or irritated eyes, which may lead to twitching.\n\nIn most cases, eye twitches are harmless and resolve on their own. However, if the twitching persists for an extended period, is accompanied by other symptoms (like vision changes or facial spasms), or significantly affects daily life, consider consulting a healthcare professional for further evaluation.",
